## Build Commands

<!-- How to compile, run, or test this project. The agent needs these to
verify its own outputs — if it edits your LaTeX, it should know how to
check that the PDF still compiles.

Include the exact commands, not descriptions of them.

Example (LaTeX paper):
  Compile: latexmk -pdf main.tex
  Clean:   latexmk -C

Example (Python project):
  Install: uv sync
  Test:    pytest --tb=short -q
  Format:  black . && isort .
  Lint:    ruff check .

Example (R project):
  Render:  Rscript -e "rmarkdown::render('analysis.Rmd')"
  Test:    Rscript -e "testthat::test_dir('tests/')" -->

[List your build/compile/test commands here.]

---

## Conventions

<!-- Your coding and writing standards. This is where you prevent the
agent from using the wrong cross-reference command, the wrong table style,
or the wrong import order. Be prescriptive, not aspirational.

The agent will default to common patterns it has seen in training data.
Your conventions override those defaults — but only if you state them explicitly.

Example (LaTeX paper):
- Cross-references: \cref{} via cleveref — NEVER \ref{}
- Tables: booktabs (\toprule, \midrule, \bottomrule) — NEVER \hline
- Math: amsmath for all equation environments
- Writing: active voice, no hedging, one claim per sentence
- Citations: author-year format via natbib

Example (Python project):
- Formatter: black (line length 88)
- Import order: isort with black profile
- Type hints: required on all public functions
- Docstrings: Google style
- Tests: pytest; test files mirror src structure in tests/ -->

[List your conventions here — LaTeX packages, coding standards, style rules.]

---

## Verification Requirements

<!-- What must be true before any output is considered done.
This is the acceptance criteria the agent checks its own work against.
Without this, "done" means "I finished generating" — which is not the
same as "correct."

State these as checkable conditions, not aspirations.

Example (paper):
- All citations must resolve (DOI or Semantic Scholar match)
- Document must compile without errors: latexmk -pdf main.tex
- Main text must not exceed 4 pages (check with: pdfinfo main.pdf)
- No \ref{} — only \cref{}
- All numbers in the text must match numbers in tables/figures

Example (code):
- All tests must pass: pytest --tb=short -q
- No ruff warnings: ruff check .
- Type checking clean: mypy src/
- New functions must have docstrings and at least one test -->

[List your verification requirements here.]

---

## Common Mistakes

<!-- Grows over time as you discover failure modes. Start with one or two
known issues; add more as the agent surprises you.

This section is the most valuable part of the file after a few weeks of use.
Every entry here is a lesson that took time to learn — encoding it means
you never have to correct it again.

Example entries:
- Uses \ref{} instead of \cref{} — always use \cref{}
- Adds \hline to tables — always use booktabs
- Writes "we show that" — prefer "X shows that" or reframe as a claim
- Suggests pip install — this project uses uv; always use uv add
- Edits results/ directory — those files are generated; never modify manually
- Invents citations when uncertain — write [CITE NEEDED] instead

Add to this list whenever the agent does something you have to fix. -->

[Leave blank initially. Add entries as you encounter recurring mistakes.]

---

## Constraints

<!-- Hard limits the agent must never violate, regardless of what seems helpful.
Keep this short — these are the lines that cannot be crossed.

Example:
- Never exceed 4 pages in main text; ask before adding content
- Never commit to main branch directly; always use a feature branch
- Never modify raw data in data/raw/ — only processed outputs in data/processed/
- Never include patient identifiers in any output
- API keys are in .env — never read, print, or include in outputs -->

[List hard constraints here.]

